      <hedline>
        <hl1>It's Only Sex</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Bart Clemente letter on Nicholas Fox Weber's August 13 article on erotic Roman antiquities recalls he and his wife were offered chance in 1969 to see fertility rite material on display at Gabinetto Segreto (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In 1969 my wife and I were at the archaeological museum of Naples and a docent asked if we were dottore. I am, in fact, a physician, and he offered a visit to see the fertility rite material, now on display as the Gabinetto Segreto, through the secret door [''Opening the Doors to Erotic Roman Antiquities'' by Nicholas Fox Weber, Aug. 13]. It would cost us 3000 lira, but we had to wait for the curator to show us the art. My wife, after seeing the exhibit, said: ''But it's only sex. What's so novel?''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In 1969 my wife and I were at the archaeological museum of Naples and a docent asked if we were dottore. I am, in fact, a physician, and he offered a visit to see the fertility rite material, now on display as the Gabinetto Segreto, through the secret door [''Opening the Doors to Erotic Roman Antiquities'' by Nicholas Fox Weber, Aug. 13]. It would cost us 3000 lira, but we had to wait for the curator to show us the art. My wife, after seeing the exhibit, said: ''But it's only sex. What's so novel?''</p>
        <p>These early people had a knack where sensuality resides. Nice article -- we enjoyed it even after 31 years.</p>
        <p>BART CLEMENTE  Akron, Ohio</p>
        <p>GABINETTO SEGRETO</p>
      </block>
